The right-wing populists in Austria: 29%
The noticeable weakening of both parties in the grand coalition and the marked strengthening of the right-wing populist parties have led, according to the first provisional results, to early parliamentary elections on Sunday in Austria.
The Austrian People's Party, in which the position of the current President, Wilhelm Molterer, is seriously shaking, has suffered particularly heavy losses.
On the contrary, the electoral leader of the Union for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), the Kärnten prefect Jörg Haider, is preparing for a triumphant return to national politics.
According to the provisional results, the country's strongest party remains the Social Democratic Party (SPÖ), with 29.8% of the vote, but losing 5.5% compared to the last elections in 2006.
Even worse was the case for ÖVP, which lost almost 9% of the vote with 25.6%.
These are the worst results of these two major parties in the post-war history of Austria and above all the literally catastrophic result of the people, who have brought about early elections.
Even at the beginning of July, when the ÖVP left the coalition, the people had a considerable advantage over the SPÖ in their preferences.
But the voters obviously punished them for bringing down the government.
Already in the first reactions to the results there was speculation about the possible resignation of the party chairman, Vice-Chancellor Wilhelm Monterer.
Observers believe that this could happen as early as Monday during the extraordinary party leadership meeting.
This development should perhaps facilitate the path towards the increasingly likely exit from the electoral result, i.e. towards the renewal of the SPÖ-ÖVP coalition.
As for the strengthening of both right-wing populist parties - the Liberals (FPÖ) won 18% and the BZÖ 11% of the vote in advance - the Social Democrats also revealed the concern of another 1999, when the populists agreed with the people to a collective government, (the FPÖ was still united, in 2005 it split from the BZÖ) which was even the cause of sanctions by the European Union.
This is clearly the case with Mr Haider, who has already said that he is ready to cooperate with any party and that he expects a return to Vienna in national politics.
The Greens also managed to enter Parliament, but fell slightly, dropping from third to fifth place among the Austrian political parties.
