Promoters record increasing bookings
It looks like it 's going to be a good winter for German tour operators .
According to one study, travel booking turnover for the coming months has increased markedly compared with the previous year - by more than 30% for the winter season.
Despite weak economic prospects, a survey shows that German travellers are still keen.
The German tourism association DRV reported on Monday in Berlin that bookings for the winter season by travel agencies increased by 31% compared to the same period last year.
According to the survey by the market research institute GfK, there are already increased booking quotas for the autumn months.
The surplus of travel agencies for October compared to 2007 would therefore amount to around 11%, the DRV reported.
The assumption for these results is the figures from GfK, which analyses monthly booking data from 1200 German travel agencies and produces statistical projections for the entire market.
It would also include travel bookings made up to the end of August 2008.
Due to the weak dollar, travel to the United States is particularly in demand, DRV reported.
Here the increase in bookings would amount to about a third.
In addition, Spain, Turkey, Greece, as well as locations within Germany, would be particularly sought-after destinations for Germans.
In particular, all-inclusive travel is highly valued, explained DRV President Klaus Laepple.
Given the rising costs of energy and food, the costs in this case would be 'better calculated for customers than for an individually organised holiday'.
Consumers could save money through, among other things, discounts on bookings made well in advance or all-inclusive offers, Laepple explained.
The summer months also reported good booking figures, with a turnover surplus again compared to the previous year - although a further study shows that the number of Germans who took a trip has decreased compared to the previous year.
