Turkey is expanding its diplomatic horizons
Long before Turkey tried to join the European Union, the European powers were eager to penetrate deep into the Turkish hinterland.
On the eastern side of the Bosphorus, perhaps 20 steps into Asia, lies one of the most beautiful relics of this failed imperial ambition.
The Hydarpasha train station was designed by German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in a neo-Renaissance style.
At least that's what the tour guides tell you.
The building stands in a row between the end of the platforms with a tower on each of its corners looking out at the world like some German provincial municipalities.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building is slightly decayed.
But once inside the ticket office from ceiling to vault, there is no doubt about the greatness of the enterprise of what was the most westerly passage.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, the Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, a latecomer to the imperial game, wanted to realize its ambitions to dominate the Middle East by means of this railway that ran from Damascus to Baghdad and beyond into what is now Saudi Arabia.
But Germany's imperial ambitions sank during World War I.
His railroads were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular Arabs.
The relative isolation from the surrounding region, created by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has passed.
British and Dominant forces advanced out of Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And there was bad news for the station at Hyderpasha.
In 1917 a munitions train exploded destroying its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then it has slowly fallen into disrepair, largely overtaken by history.
But today, this railway junction to Anatolia and all the points to the east serve - at least symbolically - to highlight Turkey's ever-growing diplomatic horizons.
The ruling Justice and Development Party - the AKP - has created a whole new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from its surrounding regions, generated by the icy borders of the Cold War, is over.
Now there is a new policy of engagement.
It is noteworthy that the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran, and of course with the European Union and the United States.
To assess the parameters of this new foreign policy, I boarded a sleeping car for the Turkish capital, Ankara, to visit one of the leading foreign policy experts of the AKP, the Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a spinning run along the tracks that produced the ancient world cadence of the famous documentary The Night Mail, I arrived in the Turkish capital - proposed as a new city for a centuries-old state intent on turning its back on its Ottoman past.
But the AKP with its well-known Islamic roots represents an exemplary shift in the Turkish consensus.
It has raised some suspicions in the West, most notably in Washington.
A taxi takes me to the AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern structure of stone and steel - built on purpose - in a developing suburb, surrounded by half-built shopping malls and power-pickers, where business executives - both men and women - meet to make contracts in the early morning.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a centre-right politician from almost any other political party in Europe.
Full suit, tie, I'm sure he had a Blackberry.
"The aim of the foreign policy party now is to reintegrate Turkey with its closest neighbours.
The Cold War was an anomaly", he tells me.
Turkey has been cut off from its interior.
Today, you must look east and west at the same time.
It wasn't one or the other.
It must be both.
"But surely at some point", I ask, "Turkey will be forced to decide?"
"Turkey", he says, "does not want to face that choice".
And then he makes a point that almost everyone I spoke to here has recited from memory: that the ties of the EU not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus, and all around the Black Sea, are as beneficial to Europe and the United States as they are to Turkey.
With Turkey on board, the message seems to be, all of Europe can metaphorically run those rail lines eastward through Asia and into the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpasha Station, after another night in the dark, I think of those two German gentlemen, Herr Ritter and Herr Conu, who had looked at this building built 100 years ago.
How surprised they would be to find that Europe's Middle Eastern ambitions may now be largely in the hands of Turkey.
And as I wait at the terminal for the ferry that takes me back across the Bosphorus, I remember that in those days Turkey was always called "the sick man of Europe".
At least then there seemed no question as to which continent should lay claim to this fascinating country.
