Mark Brown writes: as Guildford's musical director from 1962, Vernon "Tod" Handley (obituary, 11 September) had been in charge of the Guildford Philharmonic Orchestra and choir.
As a member of his municipal music scheme, the following year he founded his wonderful youth choir, Proteus.
They were supposed to be under-21/under-21, but by the time Proteus played its final in 1979, many of us were in our 20s - we simply refused to give up the choir.
The name "Proteus" (the mythological being-mutable) represented the goodwill of the choir and the ability to face everything that music had to do, whether madrigals or Messiaen, unaccompanied or with the whole orchestra.
The musical versatility produced by such a young choir was often astonishing, always exciting, and it was all because of that man's inspiration and enthusiasm for music that remained absolutely constant through the years.
How often did Tod tell us to "let the music speak for itself".
He said, "The composer knows what he wants.
It's all there, in the music.
So sing it!"
His technique in using the wand was absolutely clear and precise, though never dictatorial or flourishing.
Whatever the musical standard, it kept it higher and higher.
John Frayn Turner writes:
If a conductor was to be knighted, it would be Vernon Handley.
I knew him very well during the two decades he conducted the Guildford Philharmonic from 1962 to 1982.
Over the past 40 years or so, I have reviewed over 100 of his concerts and I can honestly say that I have never disagreed with a single one of them - and many times inspired by them.
Tod Handley had that rare combination of personal grandeur and modesty.
He hated conductors who, in his words, simply "rid around the world on one or two well-known war horses".
So many of us will miss him.
