The "bee car" to avoid collisions
In the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan has taken its inspiration from nature, and in particular from bees.
A Japanese company has created a robot that can avoid accidents by taking the flight of bees as an example.
It's the Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which is the first step towards collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.'s Advanced Technical Center have developed this tiny robot in collaboration with the Center for Scientific and Technological Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, general director of PR for Technology and Brand Management Research and Development, the BR23C is an extension of the four-area Safety Shield produced by Nissan.
This robot is intended to improve the ability to prevent collisions in the manufacturer's vehicles.
During flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space that is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
But most important are the compound eyes of bees, which can see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees, and which allow the insect to fly uninterrupted in its personal space.
To recreate this visual functionality, engineers have developed what they call a laser range finder.
This mechanism detects obstacles in front of the BR23C within a radius of two metres and with a maximum amplitude of 180 degrees, calculates the distance from the object and sends a signal to an on-board microprocessor which immediately prevents the collision.
"As soon as it detects an obstacle, the little robot mimics the movements of a bee and immediately changes direction by turning the wheels at a right angle or higher to avoid a collision.
The most obvious difference with any assisted system is that the escape maneuver is totally instinctive.
"If it were not, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot swerve up or down, nor even diagonally; it can move only in two dimensions and in the direction in which its wheels can turn and without exploiting infinite directions and ways as bees do.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, so that the little robot can avoid collisions.
"This device only needs to process information every few seconds, and act on that data.
It does not require the memorization of information or the intuitive logic of previous maneuvers, so it can run seamlessly and with only a couple of dozen KB of memory.
This may come as a surprise, but we're not talking about gigabytes of memory, and we're not talking about mega-bugs".
It is the first step towards developing new technologies for instant collision prevention, a technology that Nissan hopes will be standard in cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and more durable than the lithium ion type.
Another potential future application of this technology could be the integration of the units with a GPS satellite navigation system to bring the driver to his destination while avoiding obstacles in the path.
