Morgan Stanley opens its capital to MUFG
Morgan Stanley has announced an agreement with Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG), the first bank in Japan, to invest $9 billion in a 21 percent stake in the company, following a sharp decline in its stock market shares.
One week after the drafting of a provisional agreement, the two banks explained that MUFG would buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley's shares at a cost of $25.25 each, or a sum equivalent to $3 billion.
The price fixed is 19% below the book value of the securities at 31 August.
MUFG will also invest USD 6 billion in the purchase of convertible securities at a conversion price of USD 31.25 and ensure a return of 10%.
Morgan Stanley has stated that the overall transaction would be carried out at an average price of $29 per share, which is 28 per cent below its current price.
At 5 p.m., however, Morgan Stanley was down 6.79% to $23.07.
"This strategic alliance is an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley's transition into a bank holding company", explained John Mack, managing director of the American group.
Morgan Stanley adopted this new charter last week, which should allow it to differentiate its stock, but still bring it under the control of the Federal Reserve.
His alliance with MUFG also confirms how the current financial crisis is forcing the biggest names on Wall Street to adopt a much more cautious stance than they previously assumed.
The details of Monday's meeting also show that the deal has been modified in recent days: last Monday, Morgan had simply announced the sale of 20% of its shares to the Japanese giant for $8.5 billion.
