Rafael Correa is in Quito, we're on Monday.
To build the republic on socialism in the 21st century.
This is the joint project of Hugo Chávez of Venezuela, Evo Morales of Bolivia and Rafael Correa of Ecuador.
On Sunday, following the example of his colleagues and friends, he gave his voice to the draft of a new constitution.
This is accomplished since, according to the official results, 64% of the electorate voted 'yes' in the referendum, on a basis of 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the "no" vote was 28%, while 7% of the votes were cast as a draw and 0.7% as blank ballots.
For the draft Constitution to be adopted, it would have to get half the votes, plus one.
On Sunday, two exit polls and an estimate by a non-governmental organization announced a landslide victory for the "yes" vote, with 63% to 70% voting.
Rafael Correa had also claimed the victory of his draft Constitution in the night between Sunday and Monday.
"The Constitution has triumphed gloriously", he had assured, congratulating Ecuadorians in the governorate of Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As always, Chávez and Morales congratulated Rafael Correa, as did his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The vote, which was conducted in a calm manner by the election observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), was based on a 444-point text designed to consolidate the "new socialism" advocated by the President.
This draft constitution enshrines the power of the state over the economy, reserving to it the "development planning" of a country that lives essentially on oil extraction by large foreign companies and consequently on their currency.
Conceived by Correa, who was elected in 2006, the project also grants more power to the head of state, who can be elected for two consecutive four-year terms, and has the possibility to dissolve the assembly.
Correa has already announced his intention to take advantage of this amendment and to stand for re-election in February 2009.
The Constitution also states that health and education services are free of charge, which the president has begun to promote in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
It also prohibits the presence of foreign troops, a provision which will end the agreement between Quito and Washington to use an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for US anti-drug operations.
The 19 hostages released in Chad
An Egyptian commando has launched an assault on the kidnappers of the 11 tourists and their eight companions kidnapped ten days ago.
I'm in Cairo. I'm going to the hospital.
The 11 European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions held captive in the desert for ten days were brought back to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon, safe and sound.
In the morning, they were liberated in Chad by an Egyptian commando.
Apparently fit, the hostages arrived at the Almaza military base near Cairo International Airport at about 3:30 p.m. aboard a special aircraft.
They were immediately transferred by helicopter, without any chance of giving any press interviews, to the Maadi hospital, a residential suburb of Cairo, for testing.
They are in "good health" and no ransom has been paid "to the kidnappers", Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna said on the runway.
Kidnapped on September 19th during a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, bordering Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been rocked from hiding place to hiding place by 35 unknown kidnappers.
The group consisted of 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - and eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of Aegyptous, the safari organising agency.
An Egyptian security official said 30 members of the special forces, aboard two helicopters, launched the assault during the night, shortly before dawn.
"There was a shooting, half of the kidnappers were killed, while the others escaped", said the official who asked to remain anonymous.
He explained that 150 members of the Egyptian special forces unit "lightning" were sent to Sudan, where they would be supported by German and Italian commandos.
The Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini stressed from Belgrade the importance of the role of Italian intelligence and special forces.
We have to admit that if we have achieved this result it was thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our intelligence men, the special forces", he said, without adding further details.
He also denied paying a ransom.
The day before, the Sudanese army patrol had claimed to have intercepted a 4x4 vehicle carrying the kidnappers and killed six of them, including the Chadian leader of the kidnappers, and captured two of them.
The army claimed that the kidnappers were linked to a Darfur rebel organization, the Sudan Liberation Movement (SLA_U), a claim immediately denied by the army.
Letters - The silent majority of culture
On the front page is a debate on the financing of culture, which is the focus of the current election campaign.
That's good.
But part of our cultural life is always in the shadows.
Who will speak out against the meager sums given to the small museums, archives, archaeological digs or national historical sites that are starving?
What politician will dare to remind the federal government that it is neglecting heritage monuments and buildings?
That in Quebec, as in Canada, we don't have real laws that actually preserve our heritage?
Did you know that the French government is spending three and a half million euros just to restore the castle of Chinon in the Loire Valley?
In our American neighbours, it is the Constitution that states that the protection of heritage is part of the national culture and that the same heritage must be protected by every citizen, every political authority and every government department, and all by mutual agreement.
In Quebec, the Federation of Historical Societies of Quebec has at least 40 000 volunteers who, grouped in 211 societies for the preservation of historical, genealogical, archival and heritage heritage, are preserving, with four dollars, private archives and archaeological sites.
