When will history and heritage be given the right space?
Benelux governments nationalise part of Fortis bank
The Benelux countries are helping to partially nationalise the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis, which was the first in Europe to run into difficulties as a result of the crisis in the American credit market. The three countries will provide EUR 11.2 billion to the bank, which will also provide interest-bearing insurance in Hungary.
The governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands reached an agreement at the highest level over the weekend, including the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commissioner for Competition.
The first major crisis in the euro area in the context of the difficulties which have been debated in the international financial market for more than a year is that of Fortis, and in some respects the decisions taken in this regard may set a precedent.
Under the decision taken on Sunday night, all three states will hold almost half (49%) of the bank's stake in the country.
The bank will almost certainly sell part of its interests, including first of all the assets, mainly insurance, of the Dutch bank ABN Amro acquired a year ago.
Last week Fortis shares started with a vertical collapse, then serious signs of a crisis in the institution appeared in the second half of the week.
Analysts, however, agree that the bank, with 85,000 employees, is too big to allow itself to go bankrupt.
The bank's stock fell nearly 12% on Friday, the lowest point in 14 years.
Since January, the value of the shares has fallen by more than two-thirds.
Taking into account current share prices, the total capital value of the group is around EUR 14 billion, but according to the bank's management this value is not real.
The company's top executives blame the collapse of Fortis' shares on uncertainties in the non-European market due to the acceptance of the US $700 billion plan.
On Monday, the stock slowly started to rise again.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed the new CEO of the bank.
The financial institution has also been looking for private buyers but so far no one has come forward with a worthy offer.
The Belgian government had previously ensured that investors should not fear losing their money.
The bank's customers did not panic, and the branches were not attacked.
In Hungary Fortis has independent subsidiaries and has also acquired leasing companies.
The Fox in the Chicken coop
Life and health insurers in America, based on people's medical purchase records, often refuse to take out an insurance policy.
Privacy experts fear the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a privacy policy that the use of prescription data is always subject to the consent of the person concerned.
This program must be in independent hands, otherwise it is like leaving the chicken coop to the fox", writes the Washington Post, quoting Richard Dick, author of the program to follow prescriptions for medicines.
The insurance companies depend on the health of the potential customer for the insurance rate and the amount of the claim in the event of a loss and do not insure if they consider the risk to be too high.
In the past, the client had to undergo a medical examination and the contract was only concluded after the results of the examination.
The Commission has also been involved in the development of the European Social Fund, which is a Community instrument for the development of the social dimension.
For example, if you regularly buy large amounts of cholesterol-lowering drugs, this means that your blood fat level is practically unmanageably high and you are classified in the highest risk category.
There are various versions of the programme in the market, some of which also determine the risk multiplier, so the insurer does not have much to do other than paperwork, even if there are minor difficulties.
Among the cons is that some medicines are usable for more than one purpose, e.g. some compounds are usable against migraines or hot flashes, but they are also effective against depression.
The latter, from the insurance-commercial point of view, is a factor in increasing risk, the first two are not.
Separate companies have been set up to collect and process data and, before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies, they ask for the patient's approval.
Now the authorities are forcing them to do so even though they have not yet imposed fines for negligence.
Some companies are also processing the results of laboratory tests and linking them to data on the use of medicines to provide a more accurate picture of the health status of patients.
More and more companies have access to data and at the same time it will be increasingly difficult to control their use.
There is a separate privacy law but it only applies to health care and insurance.
There is a bill before Congress that gives the authorities oversight over companies that specialize in data services.
Richard Dick admits that this is not enough. He has therefore developed a program that links the data transfer with the consent of the data subject.
The other issue is that the person concerned cannot so much deny approval because otherwise the insurers do not make the contract.
So then the chickens are finally left to the mercy of the fox.
