EU and India double trade
As the European Union and India are trading partners, above all with each other, the agenda of the ninth summit was dominated by this issue, as well as all other global issues.
Today there will be a French-Indian summit which will deal primarily with cooperation on atomic energy.
The European Union recognises that India is becoming a major democratic power which should be given a greater say in international affairs, but the member countries have not yet been able to decide whether or not to support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
So this issue was not stressed at the ninth summit in Marseille yesterday.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, acting President of the Union, Commission President José Manuel Barroso and High Representative for Foreign Affairs Javier Solana received Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed to double trade to up to EUR 100 billion over five years.
Given that between 2000 and 2007 trade in goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this is not an overly ambitious target.
As a result, they have legally unified the 26 bilateral civil aviation agreements, so air traffic can also get started in the future.
India would like to sign the free trade agreement with the Union by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy has promised to speed up the deal.
The aim is to balance the balance because while the EU is India's number one trading partner, New Delhi is only the ninth largest among the EU's partners.
The summit focused on global affairs.
The situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan and terrorism, the latter condemned in all its forms by both sides, and called for a UN conference.
They have urged the conclusion of the Doha round on trade, even though both sides played a role in its failure.
The EU has confirmed that it will continue to pursue its energy and climate agenda, which is to reduce emissions of harmful substances by at least 20% by 2020.
India also agrees on this, as well as the fact that a global agreement should be reached at the climate conference scheduled for next year and reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 50% by 2050.
They also want to curb rising food prices and have supported the convening of an international meeting to discuss the financial crisis.
The Indian Prime Minister will travel to the French capital today where a bilateral meeting is being held to prepare for the signing of a treaty on the peaceful use of atomic energy.
In Paris, it is hoped that French firms will receive a contract worth 20 billion euros to build Indian nuclear reactors.
According to our news agency, the deal is for 15 years.
In Frankfurt, over 300 Italian publishers
Strong presence of Italian publishers at the Frankfurt International Book Fair.
More than 300 Italian publishers will be present at the 60th edition of the Buchmesse, the most important international event for the exchange of rights.
The Frankfurt International Book Fair is expecting more than 7 000 exhibitors from 101 different countries to take up the 171,790 square metres of the fair with over 403 000 titles on display and with Turkey as the guest of honour.
The Italian Government will be represented by the Undersecretary of the Ministry for Cultural Heritage and Activities, Francesco Maria Giro, at the opening ceremony of the Italian Pavilion, with an institutional presence at Punto Italia - 264 square metres of exhibition space.
The press conference will follow in Room Struktur in Hall 5.0 of the Buchmesse, where figures, trends and perspectives on the state of publishing in Italy will be presented.
According to the data, the share of books by foreign authors in total Italian production, and in particular in adult and children's books, is gradually decreasing.
Found the plane of Steve Fossett, the billionaire who disappeared a year ago.
The wreckage of the plane of Steve Fossett, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007, was found flying over the Nevada desert.
The wreckage was found on a plateau at an altitude of 3,000 meters in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammoth Lakes, on the California-Nevada border.
But there were no human remains inside the plane.
Madera County Sheriff John Anderson, who has yet to be named, said: "The plane has been located, we have sent a team, and now we have confirmation that this is the very plane Steve Fossett was flying on the day he disappeared", he said at a news conference.
The sheriff said no human remains were found on or around the plane.
The 63-year-old billionaire was reported dead in February.
The US Transportation Safety Board (TSB) said that a team of investigators was sent a few hours after the wreckage was spotted, and that they identified the Bellanca 8kcab, which had been missing since September 3, 2007, when Fossett took off from Yerington, Nevada, for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, also in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fossett's personal effects were found by a couple near their home in Mammoth Lakes.
It's two documents in Fossett's name, both issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, cash and a sweater.
Fossett's search was stopped a month after he disappeared.
The billionaire had earned his place in history through a long string of primates.
In 2002, on his sixth attempt, he became the first man to complete a round-the-world flight in a hot air balloon: two weeks of solo flight.
Three years later, he had flown around the world without stopping.
Among his many records, he has flown to an altitude of 15,445 meters, over the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
